                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/690: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-10-11T13:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 11, 1927—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>358. Your 914, October 7, 9 p.m. Your telegram to Canton approved.</p>
                <p>Is the two and one-half percent surtax referred to the so-called consumption and
                    production tax imposed October 11, 1926, mentioned in Canton’s despatch to the
                    Legation of October 8, 1926,<note n="65" xml:id="d483fn65">
                        <ref target="frus1926v01#pg_873">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1926, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 873</ref>.</note> and when was it
                    abolished?</p>
                <p>Is Department correct in understanding that new tax is ten percent of two and
                    one-half percent, namely, one-fourth of one percent?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
